  "prompt": "How do aircraft flying in formation match their speed exactly?",
  "response": "Aircraft flying in formation match their speed through several methods:\n\n1. Visual Reference\n- Pilots constantly observe relative positions of other aircraft\n- Make minor speed adjustments to maintain precise spacing\n\n2. Instruments\n- Use airspeed indicators\n- Utilize GPS and navigation systems to track exact velocity\n- Some modern military aircraft have digital formation-keeping systems\n\n3. Communication\n- Constant radio communication between pilots\n- Lead aircraft typically sets and communicates speed\n- Wingmen adjust to match precisely\n\n4. Aerodynamic Techniques\n- Use of throttle and control surfaces to make fine speed corrections\n- Experienced pilots can make minute adjustments almost instinctively\n\n5. Advanced Technology\n- Military aircraft often have automated formation-keeping systems\n- Computer-assisted speed matching and position maintenance\n- Some systems can automatically adjust speed and position\n\n6. Training\n- Extensive practice in formation flying\n- Pilots develop muscle memory and precise control skills\n- Understand aerodynamic principles of close-proximity flying\n\n7. Physics Considerations\n- Minimize speed variations to reduce turbulence between aircraft\n- Maintain safe and consistent separation distance\n\nThese methods combine human skill, communication, and technological assistance to maintain precise formation speeds.",
